    <bioghist>In the 1960s-1980s Zelda Gamson held posts of the University of Michigan Study Director and Faculty Associate at the Institute for Social Research, Professor at the Center for the Study of Higher Education, and Associate Director and Professor in the Residential College. Her husband William Gamson was Professor of Sociology at the University of Michigan.</bioghist>
    <scopecontent>Collection of newspaper clippings and journal articles on the subject of anti-war and anti-draft protests and teach-ins at the University of Michigan, and the national teach-in in Washington, D.C. organized by the University of Michigan faculty. Also includes correspondence about American atrocities in Vietnam, and paper "The University, ranking, and the submission of grades," on the subject of the Selective Service System special class rankings for male college students at the University of Michigan. The paper was prepared by a group of the Department of Economics Teaching Fellows.</scopecontent>
